ridge, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Ivybridge, South Hams district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ivybridge, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Hounton, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dymock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  See  Dimmock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dimmock","meanings":["English: habitational name from Dymock in Gloucestershire; see   Dimock  ."]}]},{"name":"or","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Jewish (Israeli): from Hebrew <i>or</i> ‘light’, a Hebraicized form of various original Ashkenazic surnames.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 柯, see   Ke   1.","Chinese: Hokkien form of the surname 胡, see   Hu   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Ke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Heng, Yong, Bin, Song, Yan, Zhi, Cheng, Chih-Ming, Chun-Yen, Fan, Fong, Gang.  Vietnamese Lan, Hai, Hoa, Le Van, Mui, Tuy.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 柯, meaning ‘bough, stalk’ in Chinese: (i) from the first element of the personal name Ke Lu (柯盧), personal name of a prince of the state of Wu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the first element of the placename Ke Ze (柯澤), the name of a fief (located in Shandong province) granted to an official in the state of Qi during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) traced back to the Qiang ethnic group in ancient western China and the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iv) adopted as a surname by the Ke Ba (柯拔) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ).","Chinese: variant of   Ge  ."]}]},{"name":"Dymoke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  See  Dimmock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dimmock","meanings":["English: habitational name from Dymock in Gloucestershire; see   Dimock  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter Dymock or Dymoke was born in 1342, in Devon, England, his father, William Dimock, was 47 and his mother, Elizabeth le Rouse, was 43. He married Margaret Tremenent about 1373, in Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters. He died in 1375, in his hometown, at the age of 33."},"et":{"1342–1375":"1342–1375","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1342–1374":"1342–1374","1362–1410":"1362–1410","1372–1408":"1372–1408","1295–1345":"1295–1345","1299–Female":"1299–Surnud","1374":"1374","1362":"1362","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1295":"1295","1345":"1345","1410":"1410","1299":"1299","1342":"1342","1375":"1375","1408":"1408","1319":"1319","about 1362":"umbes 1362","about 1373":"umbes 1373","Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England","Ivebrigge, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Ivybridge, Devon, England":"Ivybridge, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ivybridge, South Hams district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ivybridge, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hounton, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, 